english:
  title: Account of the Life and Deeds of Minister Lee, Duke of Gwangleung, Grand Commandant and Preceptor of State, Leader of the State Council
  author: Hong Gwidar
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Minister's name was Lee Keukbae, style Gyeombo, a native of Gwangju. His great-grandfather bore the name Jip, served as Registrar of the Court of Scholarly Worthies, and was posthumously honored as Left Chancellor of the State Council and Great Exemplar of the Royal Academy, with the epithet Dunchon. His grandfather, Jigjik, served as Right Counselor of the Ministry of Punishments and was posthumously honored as Leader of the State Council. His father, Insun, held the rank of Grand Commandant and Preceptor, served as Right Chancellor of the State Council while overseeing the royal lectures and the Spring and Autumn Archives, and received the epithet Loyal and Reverent.

    The mountains and waters of Gwangleung possessed singular beauty, and generations of ancestors had accumulated virtue. From these auspicious sources came five sons to the Loyal and Reverent one, each a worthy vessel of the realm. Among them, the one who received fortune's favor first and was eldest was our Minister. From birth he bore an extraordinary countenance; as a child, an exceptional spirit shone forth; in his studies, he displayed remarkable talent. He penetrated deeply into the writings of the ancient sages, and his contemporaries all recognized in him a man of far-reaching vision.

    In the year Jeongmyo of the Jeongtonb era, he passed the examination for advanced scholars and immediately advanced through the selection process, receiving appointment as Deputy Clerk of the Academy of Scholarly Worthies, advancing thereafter to the rank of Doctor of Letters. In the year Gyeongo of the Gyeongtae era, he rose to Subpresident of the National Academy and was soon transferred to Inspector of the Censorate. Serving as Inspector-General of the Imperial Missions, he proceeded to the Ming court. There was a translator who violated imperial prohibition. The Minister, applying the law strictly, issued judgment, and all present fell silent in awe. Previously, many translators had transgressed without consequence, for inspectors neglected their duties and corruption continued unchecked. Our Minister alone upheld the law unyieldingly, earning widespread commendation at the time. Before his return, he received appointment as Right Censor and Court Draftsman. The Censorate memorialized the throne: "The aforementioned official, in serving as inspector at court, successfully investigated and reported violations of law by members of the imperial entourage. We humbly request commendation." King Munjong, pleased, replied: "I shall surely remember this man."

    Shortly thereafter he was appointed Junior Aide to the Ministry of War and soon after promoted to Senior Aide. When King Sejong pacified the internal rebellion and concurrently held the positions of Minister of Personnel and Minister of War, upon observing the Minister, he recognized his exceptional worth. He memorialized to advance him one rank and would often point to him saying, "This man shall one day become Chief Royal Secretary." When corruption among magistrates and commanders in Gyeongsang Province became rampant, the King specifically dispatched the Minister to investigate. He exposed every transgression and reported them, removing the offenders, yet not a single person bore him resentment.

    In the year Eulhae, when King Sejong ascended the throne, the Minister was honored with the rank of Merit Subject for Righteous Loyalty and Valued Support, appointed Vice Director of the Royal Kitchens. In the year Byeongja, he was promoted to Director and transferred to Judge of Court Ceremonies. In the year Jeongchuk, when King Sejong personally conducted sacrifice at the Circular Mound, rewards were bestowed upon those who served. Those of rank three whose seniority was complete were ordinarily promoted to senior court rank. The Minister was among them, but the Censorate raised objection. The royal edict declared: "While others might be promoted, surely such a man as this should not be treated as a common official." By special command, he was promoted to senior rank and subsequently elevated to Counselor of the Ministry of Rites. That year, when King Sejong intended to tour Gyeongsang Province, he specially appointed the Minister to simultaneously hold his current office while serving as Provincial Inspector. In the year Muin, he came to court and was granted a horse and saddle, received one rank advancement, was appointed Vice Director of the Central Affairs Bureau, enfeoffed as Duke of Gwangleung, and granted a robe before being sent back to his province.

    In the year Gimyo, he entered the capital as Vice Minister of War, later transferred to Mayor of Seoul. That year he traveled to the Ming court to celebrate the Emperor's birthday, and upon return was appointed Vice Minister of Rites. In the year Gyeongchin, he concurrently served as Keeper of the Royal Library while holding his current post and received one rank advancement. At this time, the Ming sent emissary Ma Gam to pacify the Jurchens on the northeastern frontier. Our Minister, renowned for his diplomatic acumen, was specially dispatched to convey comfort to the envoys. At that time, Minister of War Shin Sukju, receiving orders to campaign against the Jurchen leader Nangboahan, requested that the Minister accompany him. Upon their triumphant return, he was promoted and granted slaves as reward, then appointed Inspector of Gyeonggi Province.

    In the year Sinsa, returning to court, he was enfeoffed as Duke of Gwangleung. In the year Imgo, he was appointed Minister of Personnel and served as Inspector of Chungcheong, Gyeongsang, and Jeolla Provinces, correcting the military registers. He transferred to Minister of Punishments, then to Minister of Rites. In the year Gyemmi, he went out as Inspector of Pyeongan Province. He encountered the mourning period for his Loyal and Reverent father, and in the year Eulyu, the mourning period for his mother as well. In the year Jeongha, his mourning complete, he went to court and performed obeisance. King Sejong, together with Queen Jeong-hee, received him in the inner hall, offered him wine, and immediately enfeoffed him as Duke of Gwangleung while appointing him Commander-in-Chief. He was soon transferred to Minister of War, then went out as Commander of Pyeongan Province, where he managed defense with strategic wisdom. In the year Munja, the King issued a commendation and advanced his rank. When King Yejong ascended the throne, he was appointed Right Counselor of the State Council and soon thereafter Minister of War. When King Seongjong ascended the throne, he was appointed Left Counselor of the State Council.

    In the year Sinmyo, famine struck Jeolla Province. The King commanded him to go and provide relief. The Minister devoted himself entirely to the task, and through his efforts, the entire province was saved. Upon his return, the King expressed his pleasure and specially granted him a robe. In recognition of his meritorious service alongside other ministers, he was awarded the title Vassal of Pure Sincerity and Clear Brightness in the Work of Righteous Governance, and received a rank advancement. That year he traveled to the Ming court as Imperial Birthday Envoy. In the year Gapgo, he again became Minister of War and received another rank advancement. In the year Jeongyu, he was promoted to President of the Central Deliberative Council. In the year Gihae, he was additionally invested with the rank of Protective Prince and enfeoffed as Duke and Prefect of Gwangleung.

    In the year Gyeongja, the King established a special board divided into three sections, selecting from rank two and above the most impartial men of keen judgment to serve as commissioners. They were to settle long-disputed cases concerning slaves and servants, and this was called the Board for the Resolution of Disputes. The Minister served as one commissioner, and through his discernment, all cases were settled without delay, and none complained of injustice. In the years Sinchuk and Imyin, famine again visited the people. Since the Minister had previously served effectively as Relief Envoy, saving many lives, he was commanded to concurrently serve as Vice Minister of Revenue. Indeed, he managed affairs with such wisdom that no one perished of hunger. In the year Gapchin, his rank was elevated to Grand Commandant. In the year Eulsa, he was appointed Right Chancellor of the State Council.

    In the autumn of the year Byeonggo, the King went to Hongbok Mountain to observe a hunt. The generals requested that they drive the beasts down to the shooting ground for capture. All who heard this thought it wise. The Minister alone remonstrated: "A true ruler acquires his game through righteous means. To employ deception in capturing prey is something I dare not approve." The King commended this wisdom. In the year Jeongmi, severe drought struck. The Minister took responsibility upon himself and requested resignation, which was not accepted. Soon rain fell. The King sent a court official bearing palace wine and wrote a message of comfort: "Through the Minister's art of governing the realm, we have received this gracious blessing of rain. Our joy knows no bounds."

    At this time, the kingdoms were correcting their military registers. Since the Minister had long experience in military affairs, he was commanded to concurrently serve as Minister of War. That year the present sovereign ascended the throne. The Minister, being named envoy to offer congratulations, excused himself due to age and illness. He was enfeoffed as Duke and Prefect.

    In the spring of the year Musin, the Ming sent Dong Yue, Lecturer of the Royal Academy, and Wang Chang, Imperial Attendant, to promulgate the imperial edict of enthronement. When the entourage reached Hongje Monastery, the King went to Worship of China Hall to receive them. Dong Yue and his companions criticized the kingdom for violating protocol in receiving the imperial mandate and refused to proceed. The King sent officials repeatedly to remonstrate, but they would not listen. He then sent the Minister. Observing his virtue and bearing, they showed him great respect and proceeded to promulgate the edict. The King was delighted and specially bestowed upon him a horse from the royal stables. When the envoys returned, officials escorted them to the border, and the Minister was present. Dong Yue, approaching the Minister's position, remarked: "Truly a venerable elder of Joseon."
  footnotes:
    - The Emperor's birthday was celebrated as the 'Eternal Autumn Festival' (千秋節). According to the Tang Records, the fifth day of the eighth month, being the birthday of the Xuanzong Emperor, was designated as this festival in the seventeenth year of the Kaiyuan era.
    - To 'request one's skeleton' (乞骸骨) was an idiom meaning for a high official to request retirement, expressing the wish to return to one's native place for burial.
    - The 'empty net for sparrows' (雀羅) is a figure of speech meaning the entrance gate was deserted and without visitors.
    - The Minister served through five successive reigns, holding positions in both military and civil administration. His career spanned nearly thirty years during which state power and royal favor were concentrated in his hands, yet his home received no improper petitions and he was subject to no calumnies—a rare achievement indeed.
